I've watched organic traffic collapse after business acquisitions more times than I can count. Not because the buyer did something reckless — because they did something reasonable. They upgraded the hosting. They tidied the URLs. They rewrote the homepage copy. 6 weeks later, they're staring at a 40% traffic drop wondering what happened.

Managing [44 websites across different stacks and stages](/blog/managing-44-websites-seo-data/) taught me how fragile organic traffic is during ownership changes. The patterns are predictable. The damage is preventable. But only if you know what not to touch — and when.

## Why Traffic Almost Always Drops After Acquisition

Google ranks pages, not businesses. It doesn't care that ownership changed. It cares whether the signals it relied on to rank those pages still exist. Acquisitions break those signals in six predictable ways.

**Domain migrations done wrong.** Buyer rebrands, moves content to a new domain, and either skips 301 redirects or sets up partial redirects that miss 30-60% of old URLs. Every missing redirect is a page that loses all its ranking signals overnight.

**Hosting changes that break page speed.** The old site loaded in 1.2 seconds on a tuned VPS. New owner moves it to shared hosting, load time jumps to 3.8 seconds. Core Web Vitals fail. Google deprioritises the site within 2-3 crawl cycles.

**CMS switches that change URLs.** WordPress to Shopify. Shopify to headless. `/blog/seo-tips/` becomes `/articles/seo-tips` or `/pages/seo-tips.html`. Without redirects, Google treats every changed URL as a brand new page with zero authority.

**Redirects that don't get set up.** I've audited sites where the previous owner had 200+ redirects handling old URLs, legacy campaigns, and duplicate pages. The buyer migrated content but not the redirect rules. Every old URL started returning 404s — backlinks pointing to them became worthless.

**Content changes that remove ranking signals.** The new marketing team rewrites "outdated" copy, not realising those specific phrases were the exact queries Google ranked the page for. One rewrite can drop a page from position 3 to position 30.

**GSC ownership not transferred.** The buyer doesn't get Google Search Console access until weeks after close. Crawl errors accumulate unnoticed, sitemap submissions lapse, or a robots.txt change blocks half the site from indexing.

