If you're still in the buying phase, read my full [SEO due diligence checklist for investors](/blog/seo-due-diligence-investors/) before you sign anything.

## The First 30 Days: Touch Nothing, Document Everything

The single most important rule: **don't change anything for 30 days**. Not the design. Not the copy. Not the hosting. Nothing. You need a clean baseline before you can measure the impact of any future changes.

### Day 1-3: Transfer and Verify

- **Transfer Google Search Console ownership.** Not viewer access — full ownership. Check for manual actions under Security & Manual Actions immediately. An active penalty means the traffic you bought has an expiry date.
- **Export the full backlink profile** from Ahrefs or Moz. This is your insurance policy — if links break later, you need to know what existed before.
- **Verify robots.txt and sitemap.xml.** Confirm Google can crawl everything it should, and nothing has been accidentally blocked. I've found robots.txt files that blocked `/wp-content/uploads/` — meaning Google couldn't see any images on the site.

### Day 4-7: Full Crawl Baseline

Run a complete crawl with Screaming Frog or Sitebulb. Document:

- Every URL and its HTTP status code
- All redirect chains (especially chains longer than 2 hops)
- Pages returning 404 or 5xx errors
- Canonical tag consistency
- Structured data presence and validity
- Internal link counts per page

This crawl is your before snapshot. Every decision you make in months 2-6 gets measured against it.

### Day 7-30: Monitor Without Interfering

Track three numbers weekly in Google Search Console:

1. **Non-brand clicks.** Filter out your brand name and domain variations. This is your real organic performance — the traffic Google sends because your content ranks, not because someone already knows your name.
2. **Indexed pages count.** Go to Pages > Indexed. If this number starts dropping without you making changes, something's wrong — possibly a crawl directive you inherited, or Google reassessing content quality.
3. **Crawl errors.** Under Settings > Crawl stats, watch for spikes in 404s, server errors, or crawl rate drops. These are early warning signals.

